In this paper I develop a model of information intermediation in decentralized
 matching markets.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:The-Model-of"

\end_inset

 sets up the model where short-lived buyers gradually arrive over time and
 pursue sellers by proposing jobs.
 Sellers always stay on the platform, have heterogeneous preferences over
 jobs and independently decide what jobs to accept.
 Sellers have limited capacity; when an available seller accepts a job,
 he is busy working on it for some time.
 The platform perfectly removes the coordination friction: only available
 sellers receive buyer requests.
 The assumption is motivated by the finding that most digital platforms
 have good technological means of solving the coordination problem
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
E.g.
 Fradkin 2015 finds that on Airbnb the coordination friction explains only
 6% of failed matches.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This feature of my model is in contrast to many search-and-matching models
 that have a coordination friction as the main matching friction (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BSW01,Kir09,AJK14"

\end_inset

) and keeps me focused on the matching friction that pertains to preference
 heterogeneity.
 Buyer and seller preferences over matches are not aligned: jobs unprofitable
 for sellers may be valuable for buyers, and buyers are short-lived while
 sellers are long-lived.
 
\end_layout

