Information disclosure studied in this paper has three competing effects
 on welfare.
 The first is the standard 
\emph on
Individual Choice effect
\emph default
 on the seller side.
 From an individual seller’s point of view, more information increases his
 set of attainable payoffs (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bla53"

\end_inset

).
 Holding fixed the other sellers' behavior, he individually benefits from
 more information about buyers.
 The second effect of information disclosure is the 
\emph on
Buyer-side effect
\emph default
.
 More information available to sellers reduces the platform's ability to
 induce sellers to accept buyer-valuable jobs.
 Finally, there is the 
\emph on
Seller Option Value effect
\emph default
 which arises only with non-myopic sellers.
 More information available to sellers increases their ability to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cream-skim
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the best jobs, and so creates the positive option value of rejection.
 In equilibrium, it leads to some profitable jobs being rejected, which
 hurts the joint seller surplus.
 The Buyer-side and the Option Value effect are the instances of a general
 principle that more information to sellers imposes more constraints on
 the designer and reduces the set of outcomes he can induce (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BM16-TE"

\end_inset

).
 Both the Buyer-side and the Option Value effects lead to sellers' excessive
 screening — rejection rates are inefficiently high.
 The Individual Choice effect gives a motive to the platform to release
 information while the Buyer-side and the Option Value effects give a motive
 to coarsen information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
coordination problem.
\end_layout

\end_inset

The fact that sellers can jointly suffer from more information (Option Value
 effect) owns itself to the seller coordiantion problem.
 In a marketplace where the sellers act independently, each seller keeps
 his schedule open by rejecting low-value jobs to increase his individual
 chances of getting high-value jobs.
 As a result, in equilibrium, sellers spend a lot of time waiting for the
 high-value jobs.
 Collectively, this behavior is suboptimal because all profitable jobs have
 to be completed.
 Coordination failure is attrubuted to the what I call the 
\emph on
cream-skimming externality
\emph default
: By rejecting a job, a seller remains available on the marketplace and
 attracts a fraction of subsequent buyers, who otherwise would go the other
 sellers.
 As a result, the other sellers face fewer profitable jobs and obtain lower
 profits.
 
\end_layout

